derived columns and structure
=============================

Overview
--------

This file documents columns and structure that are generated by this
repository itself, rather than by the upstream production ntuple code
described in bits/NTUPLE.

The main derived persistent object is EventListIO.

EventListIO copies selected entries from the upstream event tree and adds a
small framework-owned set of helper columns. The snapshot helpers in `ana`
can then produce flat training trees from those selected event lists.

The main bin-wise persistent object is DistributionIO.

The main assembled channel object is ChannelIO.

In the current code layout:

  EventListIO
    owns the file format and persistence only

  ana::SampleDef
    is the plain-text record used to stamp workflow metadata onto samples

  ana::build_event_list
    builds selected event lists and helper columns into EventListIO

  snapshot::...
    builds flat export trees from EventListIO selected trees

  syst::build_systematics_cache
    computes and persists rebinnable systematics caches into DistributionIO

  ChannelIO
    persists channel-level process bundles built from DistributionIO or other
    bin-wise sources

Framework-owned column naming rule
----------------------------------

Columns generated by this repository for internal analysis bookkeeping use
reserved names of the form:

  __name__

Upstream physics branches keep their original names.

EventListIO file layout
-----------------------

An EventListIO ROOT file has the following directory structure:

  meta/
  samples/<sample-key>/meta/
  samples/<sample-key>/events/selected
  samples/<sample-key>/subruns/<subrun-tree-name>

Top-level metadata written in meta/:

  dataset_path
  dataset_context
  event_tree_name
  subrun_tree_name
  selection_name
  selection_expr
  slice_required_count
  slice_min_topology_score
  numi_run_boundary

Per-sample metadata written in samples/<sample-key>/meta/:

  origin
  variation
  beam
  polarity
  subrun_pot_sum
  db_tortgt_pot_sum
  normalisation
  nominal
  tag
  role
  defname
  campaign

These fields are intended to preserve production-level workflow semantics from
an external plain-text sample definition file, for example:

  nominal
    the nominal sibling to which a detector variation belongs

  tag
    human-readable detector or workflow tag

  role
    training / plotting / validation style role tag

  defname
    production-level dataset definition name or other external handle

  campaign
    production campaign label

Selected event tree
-------------------

Each samples/<sample-key>/events/selected tree contains:

  1. all copied branches from the upstream selected event tree entry
  2. the framework-owned helper columns documented below

Framework-owned event-weight columns
------------------------------------

EventListIO always writes:

  __w__                            double
  __w2__                           double

Meaning:

  __w__
    Canonical nominal event weight for downstream use.

  __w2__
    Square of __w__, provided as a convenience for weighted variance-like
    sums and error propagation.

Current nominal-weight policy:

  data samples
    __w__ = 1.0

  external samples
    __w__ = sample normalisation

  MC-like samples
    __w__ starts from sample normalisation and then applies central-value
    physics weights when present:

      weightSplineTimesTune
      or weightSpline * weightTune
      ppfx_cv               only for NuMI samples
      RootinoFix

  Bad or non-positive component weights are sanitised back to 1.0.
  A bad final value is clamped to 0.0.

Framework-owned selection helper columns
----------------------------------------

EventListIO always writes the following boolean helper columns:

  __pass_trigger__                 bool
  __pass_slice__                   bool
  __pass_fiducial__                bool
  __pass_muon__                    bool

These are derived from the cuts preset logic using the sample
metadata and the branches available on the copied upstream tree.

Current preset names:

  raw
  trigger
  slice
  fiducial
  muon

Current preset resolution rules:

  trigger
    prefers __pass_trigger__ if already present, then sel_trigger, otherwise
    derives from software_trigger and for NuMI can use software_trigger_pre /
    software_trigger_post with the configured run boundary

  slice
    prefers __pass_slice__, then sel_slice, otherwise derives from:

      num_slices == slice_required_count
      topological_score > slice_min_topology_score

  fiducial
    prefers __pass_fiducial__, then sel_fiducial, then in_reco_fiducial

  muon
    prefers __pass_muon__, then sel_muon, then selection_pass > 0

Framework-owned truth-category columns
--------------------------------------

For MC-like, external, and data samples, EventListIO also writes:

  __analysis_channel__             int
  __is_signal__                    bool

Meaning:

  __analysis_channel__
    Canonical framework-owned channel code derived from sample origin and
    copied truth/event content.

  __is_signal__
    Lambda-channel signal flag derived from the copied event content.

Current channel codes:

  0   unknown
  1   external
  2   out-of-fiducial-volume
  10  muon-neutrino charged-current, 0 pi, at least 1 proton
  11  muon-neutrino charged-current, exactly 1 charged pion
  12  muon-neutrino charged-current, pi0 or gamma activity
  13  muon-neutrino charged-current, more than 1 charged pion
  14  neutral current
  15  Lambda signal
  16  muon-neutrino charged-current with sigma0
  17  muon-neutrino charged-current with K0
  19  electron-neutrino charged-current
  20  other muon-neutrino charged-current
  99  inclusive data

Current derivation inputs:

  nu_pdg
  int_ccnc
  is_nu_mu_cc
  nu_vtx_in_fv
  prim_pdg
  mu_p
  g4_lambda_pdg
  g4_lambda_p_p
  g4_lambda_pi_p
  g4_lambda_decay_sep

For data and external samples:

  data
    __analysis_channel__ = 99
    __is_signal__ = false

  external
    __analysis_channel__ = 1
    __is_signal__ = false

Orthogonal sample filtering
---------------------------

EventListIO currently applies an additional orthogonal phase-space filter for
some sample origins before writing the selected event tree:

  overlay
    count_strange == 0

  enriched
    count_strange > 0

This orthogonalization is applied on top of the configured event-list
selection expression.

Subrun tree
-----------

Each sample also carries a copied subrun tree at:

  samples/<sample-key>/subruns/<subrun-tree-name>

This is copied unchanged from the upstream source files named in the
corresponding DatasetIO sample.

Snapshot outputs
----------------

The snapshot helpers in `ana` build flat training/export trees from EventListIO selected
trees.

snapshot::Spec fields:

  tree_name
  columns
  selection
  overwrite_if_exists
  include_sample_id

snapshot::sample(...)
--------------------

Produces one tree per sample with name:

  <tree_name>_<sample-key>

The tree contains exactly the requested columns, evaluated from the selected
event tree for that sample.

snapshot::merged(...)
-------------------

Produces one merged tree with name:

  <tree_name>

If include_sample_id is true, the snapshot helpers define and snapshots:

  sample_id                         int

where sample_id is the zero-based index of the sample key within the current
EventListIO sample_keys() ordering.

DistributionIO file layout
--------------------------

A DistributionIO ROOT file has the following directory structure:

  meta/
  samples/<sample-key>/dists/<cache-key>/meta/
  samples/<sample-key>/dists/<cache-key>/payload

Top-level metadata written in meta/:

  eventlist_path
  build_version

Persistent systematics payload
------------------------------

DistributionIO carries persisted fine-binned systematics summaries under:

  samples/<sample-key>/dists/<cache-key>/payload

where <cache-key> is a stable hash of:

  branch_expr
  selection_expr
  fine binning
  enabled detector and weight families
  detector sample list
  cache format version
  eigenmode-compression settings

Each payload stores one fine-binned cache entry containing:

  branch_expr
  selection_expr
  nbins
  xmin
  xmax
  nominal
  detector_down
  detector_up
  detector_templates
  total_down
  total_up

and per-family summaries for:

  genie
  flux
  reint

Each family summary can include:

  sigma
  covariance
  eigenvalues
  eigenmodes

The intended workflow is:

  1. precompute a fine-binned cache once
  2. persist it into DistributionIO
  3. rebin the cached nominal/templates/eigenmodes later during plotting

These caches can be built either:

  * as part of the event-list workflow by running ana::build_event_list and then
    syst::build_systematics_cache
  * later on an existing EventListIO file by reopening it in read or update
    mode, opening a DistributionIO file, and calling syst::build_systematics_cache

When detector sample keys are not given explicitly, syst::build_systematics_cache can
recover detector siblings from the persisted sample metadata in
samples/<sample-key>/meta/ by matching detector variations with the same
nominal sample.

Detector-systematic caching stores per-variation fine templates so envelopes
can be rebuilt after rebinning.

Universe-systematic caching stores covariance and compressed eigenmodes so
rebinned covariance and per-bin RMS can be reconstructed without revisiting
the event tree.

Practical guidance
------------------

For analysis and plotting inside this repository, the most important derived
columns to treat as stable are:

  __w__
  __w2__
  __pass_trigger__
  __pass_slice__
  __pass_fiducial__
  __pass_muon__
  __analysis_channel__
  __is_signal__

For training snapshots, it is reasonable to export both upstream physics
branches and selected framework-owned helper columns, especially:

  __w__
  __w2__
  sample_id

For fast repeated plotting with systematics, treat the persisted
samples/<sample-key>/dists/<cache-key>/payload objects as the stable
cache layer rather than recomputing all universes from the selected tree each
time.

Notes
-----

This file documents only columns and metadata currently produced by this
repository.

It does not replace bits/NTUPLE, which remains the reference for upstream
production tree content.
